04039nam a22005295i 9780520928480DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209284807 a10.1525/97805209284802doi  a(DE-B1597)519702  a(OCoLC)773564946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aQH541.15.R45 .J679 2003 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a333.951a333.951531 aJordan, William R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sunflower Forest :bEcological Restoration and the New Communion with Nature /cWilliam R. Jordan. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Weeding Key Biscayne -- t2. The Challenge Of Reinhabitation -- t3. Paradigms Of Community -- t4. Awareness: Restoration As A Way Of Seeing, And As Work And Play -- t5. The Exchange: Restoration As Repayment, And The Gift Of Ecological Immortality -- t6. Value And Make-Believe: A Primer On Performance -- t7. Sacrifice And Celebration: Restoration As A Performing Art -- t8. Conservation And Community: Restoration, The Environment, And Environmentalism -- tNotes -- tSelected Readings -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEcological restoration, the attempt to guide damaged ecosystems back to a previous, usually healthier or more natural, condition, is rapidly gaining recognition as one of the most promising approaches to conservation. In this book, William R. Jordan III, who coined the term "restoration ecology," and who is widely respected as an intellectual leader in the field, outlines a vision for a restoration-based environmentalism that has emerged from his work over twenty-five years. Drawing on a provocative range of thinkers, from anthropologists Victor Turner, Roy Rappaport, and Mary Douglas to literary critics Frederick Turner, Leo Marx, and R.W.B. Lewis, Jordan explores the promise of restoration, both as a way of reversing environmental damage and as a context for negotiating our relationship with nature. Exploring restoration not only as a technology but also as an experience and a performing art, Jordan claims that it is the indispensable key to conservation. At the same time, he argues, restoration is valuable because it provides a context for confronting the most troubling aspects of our relationship with nature. For this reason, it offers a way past the essentially sentimental idea of nature that environmental thinkers have taken for granted since the time of Emerson and Muir.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aRestoration ecology. 0aRéhabilitation (Écologie). 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928480423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520928480.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles